For the "tail" queries, which are queries that only appear once or twice, Bing sees <1% of Google's tail queries but Google sees ~30% of Bing's queries. https://t.co/EGH0ciuhZW

From the prior, you can see that the most common queries in the two engines tend to be seen by both.

The tail represents ~30% of the search volume. So the net impact is that Bing sees ~50% of all search queries, and Google sees ~98% but ~48% of queries are unique to Google.

The red line is the % of Google search events that were for queries that Bing also saw, split by percentiles. 

The "head" represents the most frequent queries in Google (0-1% percentile) and the tail represents queries that are least frequent. https://t.co/7ELZKAmE92

6. TCL

Queries like ROLLBACK, COMMIT & SAVE POINT fall into this category as they're used to manage transactions in the database.

For eg: the COMMIT command commits the transaction and the ROLLBACK command rollback all changes done to a DB when a transaction fails.

5. DCL

Queries like GRANT, and REVOKE fall into this category because they're used to control access to the DB.

For eg: GRANT will assign permission to a user on a DB Object and REVOKE will remove the permission.

4. DQL

The SELECT query falls into this category because it is used to query the database and get the output of the query.

For eg: Using SELECT, we can ask any specific question to a DB and get answers.

3. DML

Queries like DELETE, UPDATE and INSERT fall into this category because they all manipulate the data in some way.

For eg: the DELETE command removes data in a table, UPDATE command updates the data.

2. DDL

Queries like - CREATE, DROP, TRUNCATE, and ALTER fall into this category because they all manage the structure of DB Objects in some way.

For eg: CREATE command creates the structure of a table, DROP command removes the table structure.

1. Introduction

The SQL commands are categorized into the following categories:

DDL - Data Definition Language
DML - Data Manipulation Language
DQL - Data Query Language
DCL - Data Control Language
TCL - Transaction Control Language

Let's see each of them in detail.

7. Characteristics

Declarative

GraphQL queries are declarative, meaning the client will declare exactly which fields it is interested in, and the response will only include those properties.

For example, if an API request the name of a movie which his id is "1" https://t.co/DPRyP0yAIK

GraphQL structures data as a graph with its powerful query syntax for traversing, retrieving, and modifying data.

Send a GraphQL query to your API and get exactly what you need. GraphQL queries always return predictable results.

1. What is it?

It is called Graph Query Language, but unlike SQL, it does not communicate directly with the databases.

It is rather a language that defines a contract through which the client communicates with the API server.
